post_text:
SCUSD will begin school online on August 3, 2020. All students that have been attending school at SCUSD you will automatically be reenrolled. If you are a new student to our district we will have an online registration and hosting drive through registration at the middle school on July 13, 15, 16 and 20, 22, 23 from 8:00 am-12:00 pm. We will be following an CDC guidelines and will have specific times for appointments. More information will be forthcoming.

The following documents will need to be provided or uploaded:
(_) Certified Birth Certificate
(_) Updated Immunization
(_) Tribal Enrollment CIB or Tribal Enrollment ID
(_) Proof of residency
(_) Guardianship or Custody court order
(_) Withdrawal Form from previous school
(_) Report Card / Transcript from previous school
(_) IEP / Psychological
We welcome everyone to San Carlos Unified School District!

Dago'tee!!‚ò∫Ô∏èüëãüëãüëãüëã To all the SCMS 8th Grade students & their parents/guardians!!

It's me, Mrs. LongKnife! Join this group I specifically created for our students, and their families!

This quarantine has us all scattered, but that does not mean we cannot keep in contact!

I greatly miss & often wonder about the wellbeing of my students/children!! This social distancing is tough, and I sincerely miss the classroom vibe!! I miss talking with, joking with, laughing with, sharing with, and learning with our children.

I pray that each & everyone of you all are healthy & doing well!
Like many things in life....'this too shall pass'....and we will all be able to see one another again!.... until then....stay hone,keep up on your assignments, be nice to one another, and know that you are all thought of & missed dearly by the SCMS staff!!

Hang In There WARRIORS....You Are All Stronger Than You Know!!

Love & Miss You All,
Mrs. LongKnife üëäüíØüíó

It's Artsy Thursday, is everyone ready to get creative?
Children develop creativity, social skills and fine motor skills with open-ended art projects where they can make choices, use their imaginations and create with their hands.

Use any materials ‚Äî from crayons to paint, clay to crafts and use #woyc20 to share photos of your creations.

Tasty Tuesday

This fun, food-themed day is about more than just cheese and crackers.
Cooking together connects math with literacy skills, science, and more.
With the rise in childhood obesity, you can encourage healthy nutrition and fitness habits at home and in the classroom.
Create your own healthy snacks and share the recipes and photos of your creations on Facebook, Twitter, and Instagram using the hashtag #woyc20.

Thank you everyone for all you do to support young children and their families in our community.
You are all heroes and Champions!!!

shared_text:
Debbie Jackson-Dennison is with Rea Goklish and 8 others.
April 2 at 5:26 AM ¬∑

I am super proud of our SCUSD administrative team! We held our first online administrative team meeting yesterday, practicing our social distancing while still getting our plans implemented! I am so blessed to have such dedicated leaders on our admin team and I truly appreciate everyone going the extra mile in this strange new way we've been forced to educate our students.
Some have quickly become pros at this as they have been meeting regularly with their staffs daily using Zoom and WebEx. Our dynamic Principals and teachers were trained and are now using an online Learning Management System, called Schoology to continue helping our students learn. Indeed, we are all on a learning curve but we are truly in this together, understanding that the only way to defeat this virus is to stay home and stay safe!

Shi≈Ç Gozh√≥√≥!
Dr. Deborah J. Dennison, Superintendent

post_text: Awesome day for our San Carlos Middle school students and staff!
shared_text:
San Carlos Apache Forest Resources Program - Forestry
January 15 at 6:01 PM ¬∑

Yesterday, students from the San Carlos Middle School visited the Yavapai Apache Cultural Center and met with Yavapai Elder, Mr. Vincent Randall. Mr. Randall shared stories about the history of the Yavapai people with the students. This trip allowed students to learn about their Apache identity and to spark an interest in learning about their family history, their language, and their relationship to nature.

This trip was in collaboration with the San Carlos Middle School, San Carlos Forest Resources Program, San Carlos Wellness Center, and Yavapai Apache Cultural Center.

Awesome day for our San Carlos Middle school students and staff!

San Carlos Apache Forest Resources Program - Forestry
January 15 at 6:01 PM ¬∑

Mr. Randall shared stories about the history of the Yavapai people with the students. This trip allowed students to learn about their Apache identity and to spark an interest in learning about their family history, their language, and their relationship to nature.

This trip was in collaboration with the San Carlos Middle School, San Carlos Forest Resources Program, San Carlos Wellness Center, and Yavapai Apache Cultural Center.

SCHS is in lockdown until further notice.
This morning the San Carlos Apache police received a call from a female who claimed to be a student, who indicated a kid was bringing a gun to school today.
All students and staff are in lock down mode while the San Carlos Apache police and SCUSD security are conducting a thorough search of all classrooms and bags. No fire arms have been found but the search is still underway.
SCUSD parents and community are asked to please stay off campus until the police complete the search.
We will notify the public with new information as soon as possible. Thank you for your cooperation and understanding.

The weeks are flying by! We will begin with Chapter 6-
"I Will Eat What is Good for Me".
Each chapter focuses on how we as a community can make better choices for our families.
Parents, you are your child's first teacher and they will model everything you do in your household.
Eat healthy and teach your children about how important it is to be healthy.
Dinner will be served.

post_text:
Parents! Grandparents! Guardians!
Join us for another class of Apache Parenting! We will finish up Chapter 4 and begin with Chapter 5 - "Taking Care of the Life that is Born".
Apache perspective of life begins at conception and being brought in the world.
Apaches believe mothers and fathers have a special connection to their unborn child.
We will discuss how thoughts, actions and planning affects children, even before they are born.
